04695nam a22006495i 9780691185088DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20182018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911850887 a10.1515/97806911850882doi  a(DE-B1597)502936  a(OCoLC)1047959816  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBS2825.52b.B43 2018eb 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a2282231 aBeal, Timothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Book of Revelation :bA Biography /cTimothy Beal. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLives of Great Religious Books ;v4900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Pale Rider: Obscure Origins -- tChapter 3. Apocalypse Not Now: Augustine's Tale of Two Cities -- tChapter 4. Cry Out and Write: Hildegard's Apocalypse -- tChapter 5. Mind's Eye: Joachim in the Forests of History -- tChapter 6. September's Testament: Luther's Bible vs. Cranach's Revelation -- tChapter 7. New World of Gods and Monsters: Othering Other Religions -- tChapter 8. Heaven in a Garage: James Hampton's Throne Room -- tChapter 9. Left Behind, Again: The Rise and Fall of Evangelical Rapture Horror Culture -- tChapter 10. Post Script: Revelation Becomes Us -- tFurther Reading -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe life and times of the New Testament's most mystifying and incendiary bookFew biblical books have been as revered and reviled as Revelation. Many hail it as the pinnacle of prophetic vision, the cornerstone of the biblical canon, and, for those with eyes to see, the key to understanding the past, present, and future. Others denounce it as the work of a disturbed individual whose horrific dreams of inhumane violence should never have been allowed into the Bible. Timothy Beal provides a concise cultural history of Revelation and the apocalyptic imaginations it has fueled.Taking readers from the book's composition amid the Christian persecutions of first-century Rome to its enduring influence today in popular culture, media, and visual art, Beal explores the often wildly contradictory lives of this sometimes horrifying, sometimes inspiring biblical vision. He shows how such figures as Augustine and Hildegard of Bingen made Revelation central to their own mystical worldviews, and how, thanks to the vivid works of art it inspired, the book remained popular even as it was denounced by later church leaders such as Martin Luther. Attributed to a mysterious prophet identified only as John, Revelation speaks with a voice unlike any other in the Bible. Beal demonstrates how the book is a multimedia constellation of stories and images that mutate and evolve as they take hold in new contexts, and how Revelation is reinvented in the hearts and minds of each new generation.This succinct book traces how Revelation continues to inspire new diagrams of history, new fantasies of rapture, and new nightmares of being left behind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691185088zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691185088423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691185088/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGru